# Component Design Rule

Use these standards when creating or updating UI components:

- Keep components single-purpose; split when one component handles unrelated concerns.
- Prefer composition over large prop-driven branching and deeply nested conditionals.
- Design stable, explicit prop APIs: clear names, sensible defaults, and minimal required props.
- Keep visual variants predictable and finite (for example `size`, `variant`, `tone`), not free-form strings.
- Forward native HTML props when appropriate and preserve `className`, `children`, and event handler ergonomics.
- Preserve accessibility by default: semantic elements first, labels for inputs, keyboard support for interactive UI.
- Avoid hard-coded business rules in shared components; inject behavior through props/callbacks.
- Extract repeated markup and behavior into shared primitives before duplicating patterns.
- Keep side effects out of presentational components; move data fetching/state orchestration to container layers.
- Write components to be testable: deterministic rendering and explicit states (`loading`, `empty`, `error`).
